PLN 105 million for video games companies from the National Centre for Research and Development
Almost PLN 105 million of funding will reach companies in the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
The National Research and Development Centre announced on Friday the results of the 3rd edition of GameINN.
Almost 30 projects supported by the NCBR include, among other things, the development of a platform for the creation of field games based on the AR engine creating a real-world map with an application for data transmission by users; a test-training platform to verify practical skills in the workplace and professional development using VR and AI technologies; an innovative game to stimulate the management of real production processes using an innovative gameplay model based on virtual world interaction with the real world using the concept of industry 4.0 – set out in the NBBR Communication sent on Friday PAP.
The objective of the GameINN Sectoral Programme is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish video gamer sector on the global market in 2023.
According to the NCBR, the Polish video game sector is already growing at a rate of 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video games market in 2016 amounted to PLN 1.85 billion and the forecast for 2019 was PLN 2.23 billion.
"A specially prepared research agenda for GameINN and already PLN 300 million for entrepreneurs in this sector program provide an important impetus for the further dynamic growth of the Polish gamedev", says the Communication.
The video game industry is an excellent example of the efficient use of the potential we have in Poland.
“The government’s incentives for innovative entrepreneurs, such as R & D reliefs, competence enhancement programmes, IP boxing and support programmes implemented by the NCBR drive innovative companies and allow them to compete more effectively on a very competitive market,” says the Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Science and Higher Education Jarosław Gowin, quoted in the Communication.
The Head of the Ministry of Science points out that the money for innovation not only comes to innovators in the form of project funding but also remains in their pockets – three-quarters more entrepreneurs benefited from the R & D relief in 2018 than in the previous year.
"The amount of deducted costs for R & D activities was PLN 1.7 billion, resulting in over PLN 300 million savings for companies benefiting from this relief.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by the NCBR in the three editions of GameINN", stresses the Deputy Prime Minister.
The director of the NCBR Dr. Wojciech Kamieniecki recalls that in the two previous competitions more than PLN 211.2 million was awarded to 78 innovative projects.
The huge interest of the III competition and the diversity of applications show that the video game industry has ideas and competences to further develop and increase its competitive advantages.
“It is particularly pleased that projects, as in previous editions, have been selected for entertainment solutions, not only as well as industry 4.0,” he adds.
In the third GameINN competition for funding of up to PLN 20 million, entrepreneurs could apply, a consortium of entrepreneurs and a consortium of entrepreneurs with scientific units.
The NCBR received 87 applications for the total amount of funding of about PLN 317 million.
The budget of the competition at the time the contest was announced was PLN 100 million, but was increased and 27 projects were awarded almost PLN 105 million.
Detailed information on the results of the 3rd GameINN competition is available at ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN Sectoral Programme is implemented under the Intelligent Development Operational Programme.
The NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to the initiative of entrepreneurs associated with the Polish Games Agreement, which includes, among others, CD Projekt, Techland, CI Games, Bloomer Team and 11 bit studios.
