The Senate adopted, without amendment, the Act on the disclosure of the assets of the families of the most important public officials and on flights of the most important persons in the State.
In favour of the amendment of the Act on the property of families of civil servants, without amendments, 52 senators voted, 14 against, three abstaining.
Thus, the senators decided to reject 12 amendments tabled during the Wednesday debate by Senator PO Sławomir Rybicki.
According to him, the amendment was intended to "civilise" and to limit the scope of the information provided in the statement on the property situation of the own children, the children of the spouse, children adapted to cases where the children remain in the joint household with the person obliged to make a statement.
The act on the transparency of the property of the families of the most important state officials, which was created at the Prime Minister's office, was passed by the Sejm on 11 September.
The rules provide, inter alia, that the Prime Minister, ministers, Members, MEPs, Senators, Presidents of the Constitutional Tribunal, the Supreme Administrative Court and the Supreme Court, as well as those who head the other state institutions, will be required to provide property information about spouses, children and persons who are in common.
Nor did the Senate propose amendments to the Act on Flights of Key Persons in the State.
It regulates what flights have HEAD status and who may be on board government aircraft with the most important persons in the country.
The Act also specifies who is responsible for keeping the Central Register of Flights.
In favour of the law – no amendments – 55 senators voted, 12 opposed, four abstaining.
According to the law, every flight of the President will be "on an official mission".
The President's flights will be able to accompany family members and others invited by the President.
On the other hand, the flight to the official mission of the Prime Minister and the Marshals of the Sejm and the Senate will only be "take place to perform tasks directly related to the function".
The Act also specifies the list of persons who may be accompanied by the most important persons in the country during the flight.
Members of the delegation may, according to the rules on board, be invited by Members, Senators, representatives of the public authorities and experts; persons providing technical, medical or organisational services; and journalists.
In accordance with the Act, in the event of doubts regarding flights by Sejm and Senate Marshals, the Head of the KPRM will request clarification.
If such doubts are not explained within the time limit set, the Head of the KPRM shall be required to notify the Head of the Sejm or the Senate of the failure to organise such a flight.
