Belgium: Brussels Airlines cancelled 105 flights due to the bankruptcy of Thomas Cook
Although the British travel agency Thomas Cook has fallen, his Belgian subsidiary Neckermann operates.
However, the company has problems.
As reported by VRT, Brussels Airlines announced that they would cancel 105 flights in October due to the bankruptcy problems of Thomas Cook.
Neckermann also fired 75 employees.
All trips with the office that have been booked in Belgium will be cancelled, but holidaymakers will be able to receive a refund.
The Gandava Court also declared the bankruptcy of three Belgian daughter companies: Thomas Cook Belgium, Thomas Cook Retail and Thomas Cook Financial Services.
At present, about 12,000 Belgians are abroad on trips purchased at Thomas Cook.
Another 40,000 people were supposed to leave the office by the end of the year.
On Monday, spokesperson Thomas Cook Belgium Leen Segers said that the company is now "fully operational" despite the announcement of bankruptcy by the British company's mother, which caused concern among employees and customers.
The office then calmed down that the customers who bought trips in it would go on vacation.
Thomas Cook – the oldest and one of the largest travel agencies in the world – announced bankruptcy at night from Sunday to Monday.
The direct cause of bankruptcy was the collapse on Sunday of the last chance with creditors and potential investors.
The creditors claimed that, in addition to the rescue plan agreed in August at £900 million, the company would raise an additional 200 million as a winter security when travel agencies usually have a lower turnover.
However, the company’s problems have been growing for several years, resulting in a debt of 1.6 billion pounds.
