Görlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for your review
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion – such an extraordinary offer prepared for visitors German Görlitz.
The aim of the action is to help combat the progressive decline in the population of the city.
Görlitz is the easternmost town in Germany.
The beautiful pastel old lady attracts 140,000 tourists a year.
However, according to The Guardian, the city is facing considerable problems.
Görlitz has the lowest wages in Germany.
The city is also struggling with a permanent population decline.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them moved to the west of the country, with a 25% fall in the city's population.
In 2013, it reached 54,000 people.
To fight depopulation, officials came up with an idea to start offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
As far as the programme is concerned, 150 applications have been made.
Two thirds of them were the inhabitants of the big cities.
The programme also interested people from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom.
“When we applied, we thought the program was supposed to convince people to move to Görlitz,” said one of the project participants.
"Now we feel that it does not matter whether we stay here after four weeks or not", he added.
The city has 7 000 available apartments, and unemployment is three times higher than the average of the country.
Although the city authorities hope that some will be carried out permanently, the main objective of the programme is to obtain the views of the participants.
The information collected from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revive smaller German cities.
"We want to know more about what people need and if they decide to move – about their motivation", said Robert Knippschild.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas to lure new residents, offering them accommodation incentives.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a program to pay promising young specialists for life and work in the city for a year.
Today such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek islands Antikythera to Candela in Italy or in the U.S. Tulsa in the state of Oklahoma.
